  56,77,"that this is indeed a noble Qur’an,",""
  56,78,"in a well-preserved Record<sup>11</sup>,","[11] i.e., the Preserved Tablet."
  56,79,"that none can touch except the purified ones<sup>12</sup> –","[12] i.e., angels. It refutes the claim of the pagans that the Qur’an was sent down by devils. (See 26:210-212). Based on this verse, many Muslim jurists held that one should perform ablution prior to reading the Qur’an."
  56,80,"a revelation from the Lord of the worlds.",""
  56,81,"Do you take this discourse lightly,",""
  56,82,"and instead [of thanking Allah] for the provision you are given, you show ingratitude?",""
  56,83,"Then why [are you helpless] when the soul reaches the throat,",""
  56,84,"while you are looking on,",""
  56,85,"when We are closer<sup>13</sup> to him than you, but you do not see?","[13] We are closer to him in terms of Knowledge and Power; Our angels are closer in person."
  56,86,"If you are not subject to retribution, then why do you not",""
  56,87,"bring that [soul] back, if you are truthful?",""
  56,88,"If that dying person is one of those who will be brought near to Allah,",""
  56,89,"then [he will have] comfort, fragrance<sup>14</sup>, and a Garden of Bliss.","[14] lit., fragrant basil. Paradise is described in the Qur’an as being pleasant to the eye, the heart, and the ear. Here it also emphasizes the scent."
  56,90,"If he is one of the people of the right,",""
  56,91,"[He will be told], “Peace be to you, for being one of the people of the right.”",""
  56,92,"But if he is one of the misguided deniers,",""
  56,93,"then he will be welcomed with scalding water,",""
  56,94,"and he will burn in Blazing Fire.",""
  56,95,"This is indeed the absolute truth.",""
  56,96,"So glorify the name of your Lord, the Most Great.",""
  57,1,"All that is in the heavens and earth glorifies<sup>1</sup> Allah, for He is the All-Mighty, the All-Wise.","[1] By praising and exalting Him far above any deficiency or imperfection."
  57,2,"To Him belongs the dominion of the heavens and earth; He gives life and causes death, and He is Most Capable of all things.",""
  57,3,"He is the First<sup>2</sup> and the Last<sup>3</sup>, the Manifest<sup>4</sup> and the Hidden<sup>5</sup>, and He is All-Knowing of everything.","[2] Before Whom nothing existed; the foremost; the uppermost. [3] Eternal after Whom nothing remains. [4] High, nothing is above Him. [5] Nothing is nearer than Him by way of His knowledge; concealed from our physical senses."
